# Downloading a corpus from project gutenberg

In this repository shows how I downloaded a corpus of selected literature from gutenberg.org (Gitenberg 2026) using the Cran package "gutenbergr" (Bradford 2026).

This project creates a curpus of books with the subject "Political science"

When I write R-code, I always start with punching the absolute path, where I want my documents to be located. Then I ask R to confirm with getwd. This is not absolutely necessary, but it gives peace of mind. In the following text, I will use the first person plural in order to include the readers in the proceses.

```{r}
#| label: my-awesome-chunk-name
setwd("/Users/ragnhildsundsbak/Documents/Learning_R/Autumn2026/")
getwd()
```

When we have installed all of the packages that needed, it is advisable to comment out the code with a \# like this:

```{r}
# install.packages("gutenbergr")
#install.packages("devtools") 
#install.packages("usethis") 
# etc.

library(conflicted) 
library(here) 
library(tidyverse)
library(gutenbergr) 
library(devtools) 
library(usethis)

conflict_scout()

conflicts_prefer(dplyr::filter()) 
conflicts_prefer(dplyr::lag())
```

The aim of the process is to prepare books as .md files for import into Obsidian vault.

```{r}
political_science_subjects <- gutenberg_subjects |>
  filter(subject == "Political science")

to_be_downloaded <- political_science_subjects$gutenberg_id

Political_science_texts <- gutenberg_download(to_be_downloaded)
```

We may check the length of the corpus with a command from R base

```{r}
length(to_be_downloaded)
```

## gutenberg_add_sections

The function identifies section markers in the text (Bradford 2026).

```{r}
P_sci_text_w_patterns <- Political_science_texts |>
  gutenberg_add_sections(
    pattern = "^(Letter|Chapter) [0-9]+",   # Multiple formats fra "details"
    format_fn = stringr::str_to_title,
    group_by = "auto",
    section_col = "section"
  )
```

## Get overview over what has been done

If needed.

```{r}
dim(P_sci_text_w_patterns) 
head(P_sci_text_w_patterns)
```

